The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, January 09, 2004 				 Apollo clinics in Bangladesh
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, Jan. 8: Apollo Health and Lifestyle Limited is opening a chain of clinics in Bangladesh. Back home, it plans to open more than 200 clinics in two years. 																								The company today announced the signing of master franchisee agreement with Starcare Healthcare Systems of Bangladesh to set up 8-10 clinics in Bangladesh. 																								Starcare is jointly promoted by Mohammad Akhtar Hossain and Farhat Khondker. The first two Apollo clinics in Bangladesh are likely to be commissioned in the third quarter of 2004 in Dhaka. 																								Apollo Health and Lifestyle is a fully-owned subsidiary of Apollo Hospitals Group. Apollo Hospitals Enterprises Ltd is a Rs 500-crore listed company. The group has a three-tier healthcare service in place comprising tertiary, secondary and primary hospitals and clinics. 																								Clinic is the primary tier, which aims to capture the market of the friendly neighbourhood doctor. At present, there are 14 clinics in operation, netting about Rs 10 crore. By 2006, we plan to have more than 200 clinics, and a turnover of about Rs 1,000 crore, said Ratan Jalan, CEO of Apollo Health and Lifestyle. 																								Already Apollo clinics are under different phases of development in Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Nigeria. It is also in advanced stages of discussions to give shape to its plans to open clinics in Qatar, Yemen and Pakistan.																								A joint-venture hospital project of Apollo is also under way in Bangladesh and Jalan hopes that by September it will be operational. At present, Apollo has 30 hospitals, spread across the nation. 
